      "web_research": {
        "results": [
          {
            "possibleIdentity": "Mel Bochner (born 1940) is an influential American conceptual artist who was active in the late 1960s and early 1970s and had a significant association with Experiments in Art and Technology (E.A.T.). In 1968, he participated in a residency organized by E.A.T. at the Singer Laboratories in Denville, New Jersey. During this residency, Bochner collaborated with scientists and engineers, an experience he documented in a series of drawings and notes known as the 'Singer Notes' (1968). These notes explored themes such as the nature of color as energy and the differences between analog and digital systems. This collaboration was fundamental to the development of his 'Measurement' series, which became one of his most iconic bodies of work. Bochner is also well-known for his 1966 exhibition at the School of Visual Arts, 'Working Drawings and Other Visible Things on Paper Not Necessarily Meant to Be Viewed as Art,' which is considered a foundational moment for Conceptual Art.",
            "sources": [
              "https://www.melbochner.net",
